<br>
     I just found this forum today, and thought I'd reply to your post - even though it is a couple months old.  I'm new here. (hello everyone!:-)<br>
<br>
     About the pin curls, I tried them on my sister, (because my hair was too long) and I had the problem of them being more twisted then curled, so sorry I can't answer your question about that, just add to your plea for help! :-)<br>
<br>
     I can tell you about rag curlers, or socks as we call them.  My mother use to put my and my sisters hair in socks,(extra mismatched ones, we always had a big box of them) and I loved it when you woke up in the morning to big bouncy curls!  The way we did it was - start when your hair is damp, not dripping, but not too dry either.  If you want, just wet it while you work by dipping your comb in water then combing the piece of hair that you are using as you go.  Start at the top/front and taking a small section of hair, (the smaller sections of hair your use, the tighter the curls)  wrap the end around a sock or rag.  Continue to roll the sock/rag right up to your head, then tie it around the wrapped hair.  You might need to make a knot, but one tight tie should do.  Continue with the rest of your hair.  I don't know if you can do this on yourself, you can try or get a mother, sister, or friend to help you.  Hope this is clear!  Now that my hair is longer, about 4 inches past my waist, I only put socks in the bottom 6in to 1foot of my hair becuase if you wrapped all my hair it wouldn't dry.    <br>
<br>
     Well, that's all for now.  I'll be back soon!<br>
<br>
Cordially, <br>
